I'm not smart enough to know what this means for Google, but as someone that now defaults to chatGPT instead of Google for searches, it will be interesting to watch them forced to adapt.

What has also surprised me is how willing I am to write additional context for a query.

Google:

INCLUDING code errors, out of my last 50 @Google  searches, I had an average length of around 6.1 words (sample size of just me).

ChatGPT:

EXCLUDING queries that include or are related to coding, out of my last 20 queries, the average length was 18.7 words.

With chatGPT, Google is now the engine that can't handle the longer queries. 

When I search on Google now, I cut down the length knowing I won't get results if I use it like chatGPT.

To the numbers...

While reading How Google Works, it really stood out when they mentioned that users' query length was increasing by 5% per year. 

So I did a quick comparison between my search lengths on @Google and @OpenAI's chatGPT to see how much of a one-year change this is for search length.
